1418":"1418","1428":"1428","about 1395":"about 1395","Postling, Kent, England":"Postling, Kent, England","of Honeywood, Postling, Kent, England":"Postling, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Honeywood,Postling,Kent,England":"Postling, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Honeywood, Postling, Kent, England":"Postling, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":59,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Honiwood was born about 1396, in Postling, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, Allan De Honywood, was 33 and his mother, Mrs Alan De Honywood, was 22. He married Catherine Caseborne in 1418, in Postling, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"ABT 1396–":"umbes 1396–Surnud","1396–Male":"1396–Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1428–1463":"1428–1463","1364–1401":"1364–1401","1376–Female":"1376–Surnud","1440":"1440","1396":"1396","1401":"1401","ABT 1396":"umbes 1396","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1376":"1376","1364":"1364","1463":"1463","1418":"1418","1428":"1428","about 1395":"umbes 1395","Postling, Kent, England":"Postling, Kent, England","of Honeywood, Postling, Kent, England":"Postling, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Honeywood,Postling,Kent,England":"Postling, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Honeywood, Postling, Kent, England":"Postling, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1396–":"noin 1396–Kuollut","1396–Male":"1396–Kuollut","1400–Female":"1400–Kuollut","1428–1463":"1428–1463","1364–1401":"1364–1401","1376–Female":"1376–Kuollut","1440":"1440","1396":"1396","1401":"1401","ABT 1396":"noin 1396","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1376":"1376","1364":"1364","1463":"1463","1418":"1418","1428":"1428","about 1395":"noin 1395","Postling, Kent, England":"Postling, Kent, England","of Honeywood, Postling, Kent, England":"Postling, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Honeywood,Postling,Kent,England":"Postling, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Honeywood, Postling, Kent, Engl